title SLC go-to-market — flagship first for wealthy early adopters, then scale to value/pro/flagship tiers
prompt Keaton pivoted: instead of budget, shoot for the highest performance money can currently buy; early users will be wealthier, giving the highest chance at the most lovable experience when cost is no object; then take the lessons to scale to sustainable Glowphones with value, pro, and flagship tiers.
think read this as a decisive ordering reversal, not a contradiction: the prior turn's budget used-Pixel reach tier was right about the DEVICE reasoning but wrong about the ORDER. So per accrete-never-break, I did not delete the Reach Tier section -- I repositioned it as the value tier (arriving last) and added a Go-to-Market section above it that supersedes the budget-first framing.
think justified flagship-first on three converging grounds rather than one: SLC leads with lovable (the most lovable broadcast is easiest to reach when hardware imposes no ceiling); Zero-to-One niche domination (delight a premium niche completely before expanding, and wealthy early adopters become the proof and word-of-mouth that funds the descent); and lessons transfer downward not upward (build at the top where the ceiling is highest, harvest lessons, then meet more people where they are).
think grounded the flagship device in dated July 2026 research: the Pixel 10 Pro XL is the highest-performance sovereign-capable device -- Tensor G5, 16GB, 6.8" 120Hz LTPO OLED, pro triple camera with 8K video (ideal for a lovable broadcast), Titan M2 + ARM MTE, Wi-Fi 7, IP68, 7-year updates, GrapheneOS production-supported with an unlockable bootloader and a 15-30 min web installer. So it is both highest-performance AND fully sovereign/de-Googled/hardened.
think named one honest thing so the flagship is justified for the right reason: for GrapheneOS security itself, the Pro-XL premium buys comfort/camera/display, not a fundamentally safer device than the cheaper Pixel 10 (same G5, Titan M2, MTE). So the flagship earns its place on lovability -- the experience -- which is exactly the stated goal, not on security theater.
think laid the three sustainable tiers (flagship now for wealthy early adopters; pro = mid-flagship or the repairable Fairphone; value = the budget used Pixel, arriving last) and named that the value tier is the destination, reached with lovability already proven, so the affordable phone inherits an experience worth loving rather than a compromised one.
think this pivot did not touch the green L1 core or the build plan -- Pool P0 remains the unblocking build step regardless of which device tier ships first. Go-to-market ordering is a market decision layered over the same technical spine.
obs the user did not say "send" or "ship" this turn, so this is committed to the branch and pushed, held from main awaiting the send word -- consistent with the convention.
file active-designing/20260715-194500_the-slc-product-glow-on-capable-hardware.md -- Go-to-Market section added (flagship-first, Pixel 10 Pro XL, three tiers); the Reach Tier section repositioned as the value tier with a dated note, not deleted
file active-designing/README.md -- index row meaning updated to the flagship-first go-to-market
